\section{Regulatory conventions}{

Standard pharma house styles recommend:
\itemize{
\item Use spanning headers \strong{only when necessary}. Avoid them for simple
two-arm tables where the column label already identifies the treatment
group.
\item When used, the span label typically carries the \strong{treatment arm name}
or \strong{timepoint period}, while the individual column labels carry the
dose level and N (e.g. \code{"10 mg\\n(N=45)"}).
\item Common patterns:
\itemize{
\item Single-level span grouping dose arms under a compound name:
\code{"Zomerane" = c("low_dose", "high_dose")}
\item Two-level span: dose arms at level 1, compound at level 2.
\item Timepoint spans: \code{"Week 12" = c("w12_n", "w12_pct")}.
}
